{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tightly coupling your agent code to a single AI vendor's SDK makes every future migration a re-write. A model abstraction layer inserts a thin interface between your agents and the underlying vendor SDKs, so swapping or adding a vendor becomes a matter of writing one new adapter rather than touching every agent."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A model abstraction layer (MAL) is a software boundary that defines a vendor-agnostic interface for language model calls and implements that interface once per vendor. The abstraction covers the three variation points between vendors: request schema, response schema, and streaming protocol."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Enterprise agentic platforms are built over multi-year horizons. The vendor landscape changes\u2014models improve, pricing shifts, compliance requirements evolve. A platform without an abstraction layer accumulates vendor-specific code across dozens of agents. The MAL pays off the first time you need to add a second vendor or swap out the primary model, which typically happens within 12\u201318 months of initial deployment."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Benefits"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Vendor portability:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " swap or add a vendor without touching agent code."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Consistent observability:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " instrument once in the abstraction layer; all vendors emit identical traces."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Uniform retry logic:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " implement once, applies to all vendors."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Testability:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " mock the abstraction interface to unit-test agent logic offline."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Lowest common denominator risk:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the interface may not expose vendor-specific capabilities without extensions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Maintenance overhead:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " each vendor SDK update may require adapter updates."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Abstraction leakage:",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " context window sizes and token counting differ per vendor; these must be exposed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interface design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Define the minimal contract: a complete() method that accepts a list of messages and returns a string, and a complete_stream() method that yields string deltas. Keep the interface narrow\u2014only add a method when it represents a capability all vendors share."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adapter implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each adapter translates between the canonical interface and the vendor SDK. The adapter owns all vendor-specific knowledge: the OpenAI adapter knows that tool calls arrive in message.tool_calls; the Anthropic adapter knows they arrive in content blocks of type tool_use. Adapters are the only place where vendor SDK imports appear."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Vendor-specific extensions"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Some vendor capabilities have no cross-vendor equivalent. Handle these through optional extension interfaces that adapters may implement. Agent code checks isinstance(client, ExtendedThinkingMixin) before calling the extended method\u2014preserving portability for agents that do not need the feature."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adapter versioning and compatibility contract"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Vendor SDK minor versions sometimes introduce breaking changes to response types. Pin each adapter to a specific SDK version range in your dependency manifest and test upgrades in isolation before rolling them to production. Introduce a VENDOR_ADAPTER_VERSION constant in each adapter file and expose it as an adapter property. When an incident traces back to a vendor SDK change, the version constant lets you immediately identify which adapter is affected without scanning release notes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Observability integration in the base class"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most consistent place to add latency and token-count instrumentation is the base class, not each adapter. Implement a _trace_complete() wrapper in LLMClient that records a start timestamp, calls the adapter's _do_complete() method, records end timestamp and token counts from the response metadata, and emits an OpenTelemetry span. Adapters override _do_complete() rather than complete(). This pattern guarantees that no vendor ever bypasses instrumentation, even if an adapter developer forgets to add tracing to a new method."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture diagram"
          }
        ]
      },
